CDs have emerged as promising FL nanomaterials for the fabrication of FL biosensors, due to their superior properties, like great biosafety, facile preparation, and modification, and excellent water solubility and especially adjustable multi-color FL properties [24–26] which favor the synthesis of intrinsic dual emissive carbon dots to fabricate ratio-metric FL biosensor. The intrinsic dual emissive CDs (λ
                     em = 650 and 680 nm) are synthesized by hydrothermal and post-reducing strategy. With the addition of Zn2+, the FL intensity at 650 nm increases obviously while that at 680 nm progressively decreases. As for the presence of Mn2+, though the FL intensity at 680 nm declines obviously, the FL intensity at 650 nm nearly keeps constant (Scheme 1
                     ). These phenomena provide direct principles for separate detecting of Zn2+ and Mn2+ with ratio-metric mode.

Based on the above results, this analytical system of re-CDs possesses several merits, such as super-high sensitivity, excellent selectivity, and great anti-interference ability, which inspire us to apply the re-CDs to the detection of Zn2+ and Mn2+ in practical samples. To evaluate the reliability of the re-CDs-based ratio-metric FL probe to be applied in complex biological samples, the recovery assay for Zn2+ and Mn2+ in human serum samples was conducted. As shown in Table 1
                        , the excellent recoveries of Zn2+ in the range from 99.5 to 109.1% with the relative standard deviation (RSD) less than 2.0% were obtained. Moreover, recoveries of all Mn2+ in spiked samples are between 101.1 and 107.2% with relative standard deviation lower than 5.0 (Table 1). On the other hand, the recoveries of Zn2+ in sandy lake water are determined to be within 95.6%–107.6% with RSD less than 1.35%. And the superior recoveries of Mn2+ in spiked lake water with value between 98.0% and 108.0% with RSD less than 4.94% are realized (Table 2
                        ). These results further prove that the presented ratio-metric FL probe can be employed to monitor Zn2+ and Mn2+ in complex samples with satisfactory results. The high sensitivity of re-CDs in spiked serum samples, revealed through an extremely low limit of detection, opens their potential applicability as sustainable, biocompatible, and simple-to-use optical sensors.
